t The Julian law (de maritandis ordinibus), for the discouragement of oelibacy and the regulation of marriage, was among the social and moral refomas aimed at by Augustus, and passed the year before the celebra· tion of the Secular games. It appears to have been a law well meant, but in some respects singularly unwise and impracticable The unmar· ried person could not succeed to a legacy unless he married within a hundred days after the bequest Fancy poor Horace himself condemned to decide between forfeiting the bequest of a villa at Tarentum or marry- ing some Glycera or Pyrrha!
